{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519531"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13034"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13034"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.75,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51990"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"282"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42841"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51990"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with ongoing seizures. According to her husband, she experienced a witnessed generalized tonic clonic seizure at home that lasted for approximately 5-6 minutes before they called emergency services. Her medical history includes epilepsy for which she is on valproate but is non-compliant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the emergency department, she is still actively seizing, the medical team promptly established intravenous access, ensured adequate oxygenation, and initiated monitoring of vital signs. The initial steps for managing status epilepticus were taken, including administering midazolam twice but no improvement yet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phenobarbital","Propofol","Phenytoin","Repeat midazolam","Lacosamide"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of status epilepticus not responding to a benzodiazepine (midazolam) given twice. The most appropriate next step of management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ephenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E, second line antiepileptic. Status epilepticus is a seizure with 5 minutes or more of continuous clinical and/or electrographic seizure activity or recurrent seizure activity without recovery between seizures. It is usually given 15-18 mg/kg IV at a rate of 50mg/min. Other drugs that can be used include \u003Cstrong\u003Evalproate (\u003C/strong\u003E40mg/kg) or \u003Cstrong\u003Elevetiracetam (\u003C/strong\u003E60mg/kg).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E more than twice is not indicated. Guidelines suggest repeating a benzodiazepine twice and if seizure still persists then giving a second line antiepileptic is advised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenobarbital\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-acting barbiturate that acts as an antiepileptic medication. It is commonly used for refractory status epilepticus that does not respond to benzo+ another second line drug. It works by enhancing the inhibitory effects of the neurotransmitter GABA, thereby reducing seizure activity. Phenobarbital can be administered intravenously in a loading dose to quickly control seizures. It has a slow onset of action, so its full effect may take several minutes to hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropofol\u003C/strong\u003E is a short-acting sedative-hypnotic agent that is used in the management of refractory status epilepticus. It acts as a GABA agonist, producing sedation and antiepileptic effects. Propofol is usually administered intravenously as a continuous infusion. It has a rapid onset of action and can quickly stop seizures. However, propofol requires close monitoring of respiratory function and blood pressure, as it can cause respiratory depression and hypotension. It is typically used in intensive care settings due to its potential for profound sedation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELacosamide\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiepileptic medication that works by enhancing the slow inactivation of voltage-gated sodium channels. While lacosamide may have efficacy in managing super refractory seizures, it is not typically considered a first-line or second-line treatment for status epilepticus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phenytoin is the most appropriate choice after giving benzodiazepine twice for status epilepticus."],"references":["Outin, Herv\u00e9a; Lefort, Huguesb; Peigne, Vincentc;  the French Group for Status Epilepticus Guidelines. Guidelines for the management of status epilepticus. European Journal of Emergency Medicine 28(6):p 420-422, December 2021.","Heuser K, Olsen KB, Ulvin LB, et al. Modern Treatment of Status Epilepticus in Adults. In: Czuczwar SJ, editor. Epilepsy [Internet]. Brisbane (AU): Exon Publications; 2022 Apr 2.","https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Afebrile_seizures/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-01T13:26:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-01T13:28:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51990"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags